10.3: Color histograms

Adrian

The previous lesson discussed the most basic type of image descriptor — color channel statistics. Today we are going to review a type of basic image descriptor, but one that is substantially more powerful and is pervasive across all of computer vision in some form of another. I’m talking about the histogram. Specifically, the color histogram.

Just as our basic color channel statistics (i.e. the mean and standard deviation) characterize the color distribution of an image, so does a color histogram. But unlike a the mean and standard deviation which attempt to summarize the pixel intensity distribution, a color histogram explicitly represents it! In fact, a color histogram is the color distribution!

We’ll still be operating under the same assumption that images with similar color distributions contain equally similar visual contents — this assumption may or may not hold in your particular application. For many computer vision systems (especially for those operating under controlled lighting conditions) color histograms become an extremely valuable and powerful image descriptor.

Instead of building another example to rank a dataset of images in terms of their similarity as we did in the color channel statistics lesson, we’re actually going to apply a little machine learning today. We’re going to take another small dataset of images — but instead of ranking, we are going to cluster and group them into two distinct classes using color histograms.

Imagine being able to take the photos from your last family vacation and automatically group them into specific events and places based only on the image contents. In essence, that’s exactly what we will be doing today.

Objectives:

We have two primary objectives today:

  1. Learn how histograms can be used as image descriptors.
  2. Apply k-means clustering to cluster color histogram features.

Color histograms

At this point in the course, you should know what a histogram, specifically, a color histogram, is. But we’ll briefly review them just in case.

Simply put, a color histogram counts the number of times a given pixel intensity (or range of pixel intensities) occurs in an image. Using a color histogram we can express the actual distribution or “amount” of each color in an image. The counts for each color/color range are then used as our feature vector.

Note: If you need a refresher on histograms, I suggest going back and reading the Histograms lesson for some more background.

As image descriptors, color histograms tend to be quite powerful. If we decided to utilize a 3D color histogram with 8 bins per channel, we could represent any image of any size using only 8 x 8 x 8 = 512 bins, or a feature vector of 512-d. The size of an image has no effect on our output color histogram — although it’s wise to resize large images to more manageable dimension to increase the speed of the histogram computation.

I think it’s best now to jump into an example and see exactly how we can extract color histograms from images and use them as feature vectors.

For this example we are going to use a small subset of photos I took on a vacation out to the western part of the United States a few weeks ago. I was able to visit two amazing National Parks, including the Grand Canyon and Antelope Canyon.

Here are 5 images captured from the rim of the Grand Canyon:

Figure 1: 5 images captured from the rim of the Grand Canyon.

And here are 5 images from inside Antelope Canyon:

Figure 2: 5 images captured from inside Antelope Canyon.

This is a small dataset — only 10 images. It would be absolutely trivial for us to inspect these images and determine which image belonged to which National Park. But in reality, I have over 2,000 photos from that vacation. Manually sorting those images into the correct categories would be a time consuming and tedious process.

So what if we could apply some computer vision and machine learning to automatically categorize these photos? It would save time. It would be efficient. And it could be leveraged for other image datasets as well.

That’s exactly what we’re going to do. We’re going to define the type of histogram we want to extract, then extract our color histograms from each image, and then apply k-means clustering to cluster and group the vacation photos into their respective categories — and all of this will be done automatically for us.

We’ll be using the k-means algorithm many, many times inside this course, especially when we start building image search engines. But for the time being, let’s stick with a quick overview so we can keep this lesson moving forward.

Sidebar: K-means clustering

So what exactly is k-means?

K-means is a clustering algorithm.

The goal is to partition n data points into k clusters. Each of the n data points will be assigned to a cluster with the nearest mean. The mean of each cluster is called its “centroid” or “center”:

Figure 3: An example of k-means separating 2-d data into 3 distinct clusters.

Overall, applying k-means yields k separate clusters of the original n data points. Data points inside a particular cluster are considered to be “more similar” to each other than data points that belong to other clusters.

In this particular lesson, we will be clustering the color histograms extracted from the images in our dataset — but in reality, you could be clustering any type of feature vector.

Histograms that belong to a given cluster will be more similar in color distribution than histograms belonging to a separate cluster.

One caveat of k-means is that we need to specify the number of clusters we want to generate ahead of time. There are algorithms that automatically select the optimal value of k, but these algorithms are outside the scope of this post. For the time being, we’ll be manually supplying a value of k=2 to separate the two classes of images.

Alright, back to the example…

Before we can cluster vacation photo dataset into two distinct groups, we first need to extract color histograms from each of the 10 images in the dataset. With that in mind, let’s go ahead and define the directory structure of this project:

First we’ll be defining our image descriptor inside the descriptors  sub-module of the pyimagesearch  package. And inside the descriptors  sub-module, we’ll create a LabHistogram  class to extract color histograms from images in the L*a*b* color space:

labhistogram.py

# import the necessary packages
import cv2
import imutils
 
class LabHistogram:
def __init__(self, bins):
# store the number of bins for the histogram
self.bins = bins
 
def describe(self, image, mask=None):
# convert the image to the L*a*b* color space, compute a histogram,
# and normalize it
lab = cv2.cvtColor(image, cv2.COLOR_BGR2LAB)
hist = cv2.calcHist([lab], [0, 1, 2], mask, self.bins,
[0, 256, 0, 256, 0, 256])
 
# handle if we are calculating the histogram for OpenCV 2.4
if imutils.is_cv2():
hist = cv2.normalize(hist).flatten()
 
# otherwise, we are creating the histogram for OpenCV 3+
else:
hist = cv2.normalize(hist,hist).flatten()
 
# return the histogram
return hist

Line 5 defines our LabHistogram  image descriptor class taking only a single, required argument — the number of bins  in our 3D histogram.

I tend to define my image descriptors as classes rather than functions, because you rarely ever extract features from a single image alone. You instead extract features from an entire dataset of images. Furthermore, you expect that the features extracted from all images utilize the same parameters — in this case, the number of bins for the histogram. It wouldn’t make much sense to extract a histogram using 32 bins from one image and then 128 bins for another image if you intend on comparing them for similarity or clustering them into groups of similar images.

The actual feature extraction takes place inside the describe  function on Line 10, which accepts two arguments: the image  we want to extract features from and an optional mask , which would allow us to extract features from only the parts of an image that interest us.

The first step is to convert our image from the RGB color space to the L*a*b* color space on Line 13. From there, we apply our knowledge of histograms from the Histograms lesson to compute the 3D histogram on Line 14 and 15, followed by normalizing it on Lines 18-23 (depending on your OpenCV version).

It’s very important that we perform this normalization step. If we did not, then images with the exact same contents but different sizes would have dramatically different histograms. Instead, by normalizing our histogram we ensure that the width and height of our input image has no effect on the output histogram.

Finally, Line 26 returns our histogram feature vector to the calling function.

So at this point you might be wondering: why we are using the L*a*b* color space?

As I mentioned back in the Lighting and color spaces module, the Euclidean distance between two colors in the L*a*b* has perceptual and noticeable meaning. And since the k-means clustering algorithm assumes a Euclidean space, we will get better clusters by using the L*a*b* color space than RGB or HSV.

Now that we have our LabHistogram  image descriptor defined, let’s see how we can use it to extract color features from images. Open up a new file, name it cluster_histograms.py , and insert the following code:

cluster_histograms.py

# import the necessary packages
from pyimagesearch.descriptors.labhistogram import LabHistogram
from sklearn.cluster import KMeans
from imutils import paths
import numpy as np
import argparse
import cv2
 
# construct the argument parse and parse the arguments
ap = argparse.ArgumentParser()
ap.add_argument("-d", "--dataset", required=True,
help="path to the input dataset directory")
ap.add_argument("-k", "--clusters", type=int, default=2,
help="# of clusters to generate")
args = vars(ap.parse_args())

The import statements here are fairly standard. We’ll be utilizing our LabHistogram  to (obviously) describe our images. And we’ll be using the scikit-learn implementation of k-means to cluster our color histograms. Otherwise, our imports are as to be expected.

However, I do want to draw your attention to the command line arguments on Lines 10-15:

  • --dataset : This is the path to the directory containing our vacation photos that we are going to cluster.
  • --clusters : As I mentioned above, we need to supply the value of k — the number of clusters to generate — to the k-means algorithm before we can actually cluster our images. The --clusters  argument controls the number of clusters. In this case, we’ll default k=2 since we are only trying to separate images into two separate groups.

Now, let’s extract color histograms from our dataset:

cluster_histograms.py

# initialize the image descriptor along with the image matrix
desc = LabHistogram([8, 8, 8])
data = []
 
# grab the image paths from the dataset directory
imagePaths = list(paths.list_images(args["dataset"]))
imagePaths = np.array(sorted(imagePaths))
 
# loop over the input dataset of images
for imagePath in imagePaths:
# load the image, describe the image, then update the list of data
image = cv2.imread(imagePath)
hist = desc.describe(image)
data.append(hist)
 
# cluster the color histograms
clt = KMeans(n_clusters=args["clusters"])
labels = clt.fit_predict(data)

We instantiate our LabHistogram  image descriptor on Line 18, indicating that we are utilizing 8 bins per L*, a*, and b* channels respectively in our 3D histogram. Using 8 bins per channel will yield us a feature vector of 8 x 8 x 8 = 512-d.

We’ll also initialize a list, data  (Line 19), to store the color histograms extracted from our image. Unlike the previous lesson on color channel statistics, we do not need a dictionary datatype since we are not comparing and ranking images — just clustering and grouping them togther.

Lines 22 and 23 grab the paths to our images in the vacation photo dataset, which we start looping over on Line 26.

Lines 28-30 handle applying our LabHistogram  image descriptor and updating the data  list.

Now that we have all of our color features extracted, we can cluster the feature vector using the k-means algorithm on Lines 33 and 34. We initialize k-means using the supplied number of clusters via command line argument. And a call to clt.fit_predict  not only performs the actual clustering, but performs the prediction as to which histogram (and thus which associated image) belongs to which of the 2 clusters.

To view the output of our clustering, we’ll just need a little bit more code:

# loop over the unique labels
for label in np.unique(labels):
# grab all image paths that are assigned to the current label
labelPaths = imagePaths[np.where(labels == label)]
 
# loop over the image paths that belong to the current label
for (i, path) in enumerate(labelPaths):
# load the image and display it
image = cv2.imread(path)
cv2.imshow("Cluster {}, Image #{}".format(label + 1, i + 1), image)
 
# wait for a keypress and then close all open windows
cv2.waitKey(0)
cv2.destroyAllWindows()

Now that we have our color histograms clustered, we need to grab the unique IDs for each cluster. This is handled by making a call to np.unique  on Line 37, which returns the unique values inside a list.

For each unique label , we need to grab the image paths that belong to the cluster (Line 39). And for each of the images that belong to the current cluster, we load and display the image to our screen (Lines 42-49).

Let’s go ahead and see our vacation photo image cluster system in action:

cluster_histograms.py
Python
1
$ python cluster_histograms.py --dataset dataset

After the color features are extracted and subsequently clustered, you should see the images belonging to the first cluster:

Figure 4: By extracting color histograms and k-means clustering, we are able to correctly group all of the Antelope Canyon photos together.

Notice how the images inside Cluster #1 are all from to the Antelope Canyon.

Similarly, all images inside Cluster #2 are all from the Grand Canyon:

Figure 5: Our Grand Canyon photos are all placed into the same, but different cluster, separate from the Antelope Canyon grouping.

Note: When you run this algorithm yourself, you may notice that Cluster #1 contains the photos from the Grand Canyon and Cluster #2 contains images from Antelope Canyon. If this happens, no worries! K-means is an example of a stochastic algorithm, meaning that it relies on a certain randomness when selecting the initial histograms to cluster on. It is fully possible for the cluster IDs themselves to change, but the images will still belong to their respective characters.

As you can see from the results above, by using only color histograms and a tiny bit of machine learning we were able to automatically categorize our vacation photo dataset.

But that’s not all color histograms (and histograms in general) are good for. Once we get to the Content-Based Image Retrieval module we’ll be leveraging histograms in some form or capacity in nearly every single topic. The purpose of this lesson was mainly to introduce you to utilizing color histograms to characterize the color distribution of an image — as well as demonstrate a real-world use for color histograms.

Summary

We already reviewed color histograms in a previous lesson. But up until this point, we mainly thought of histograms as a way to visualize the color distribution of an image. In reality, color histograms are much, much more useful than simple visualizations.

Inside this lesson we found that we can treat color histograms as feature vectors that characterize the color distribution of an image. Then, by clustering our color histograms, we were able to (automatically) create groups of images that have have similar color distributions.

So far in this module we have reviewed two methods to describe the color of an image: color channel statistics and color histograms. But what if we wanted to quantify the texture of an image? Or the shape of an object in an image?

No worries — in the upcoming lessons we will start to review texture and shape based descriptors, eventually ending with a complete and exhaustive overview of keypoint detectors and local invariant descriptors such as SIFT and SURF.
